  "prompt": "Is tamil a waste language?",
  "response": "No, Tamil is not a waste language. It is one of the oldest living languages in the world, with a rich literary tradition that dates back over 2,000 years. Tamil is spoken by millions of people primarily in the Indian state of Tamil Nadu and the union territory of Puducherry, as well as in Sri Lanka, Singapore, Malaysia, and diaspora communities around the world.\n\nTamil has a vast body of classical literature, including the Sangam literature, which is considered a treasure trove of ancient poetry and prose. The language has also made significant contributions to art, culture, music, and cinema. Tamil cinema, often referred to as \"Kollywood,\" is a major film industry in India and has a global audience.\n\nMoreover, Tamil is recognized as a classical language by the Government of India, acknowledging its historical significance and cultural heritage. It is also one of the official languages of India and Sri Lanka.\n\nDismissing any language as \"waste\" undermines the cultural identity and heritage of its speakers. Every language has intrinsic value and plays a crucial role in preserving the history, traditions, and collective memory of its community. Respecting and preserving linguistic diversity is essential for fostering understanding and appreciation among different cultures.",
